        <h3>Tourist Precautions</h3>
        <h1>Illegal Taxi</h1>
      <img src="/taxiChina.jpg" alt="Directions on narrow and steep walkways" class="smaller-image">
      <p>
        illegal taxi services, often referred to as "black taxis," have been a concern in various parts of China. These unauthorized taxi services operate outside the legal framework and regulations established by local transportation authorities. They often lack proper licensing, insurance, and safety measures, which can pose risks to both passengers and drivers.
        Passengers using illegal taxis may be at risk due to the absence of safety standards and proper driver training. In case of accidents, passengers might not have access to proper insurance coverage or legal recourse.
        
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>Do not be afraid to ask the local regarding the transportation, who knows better than the people who live there. Do your own research about the illegal taxi criteria and trust your insting on it.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Tap Water</h1>
        <img src="/tapWaterChina.jpg" alt="Littering" class="smaller-image">
      <p> Tap water safety can vary across different regions of China. In some areas, tap water is safe for drinking, while in others, it's recommended to drink bottled or boiled water. 
          We recommend you not to drink the tap water in every regions of China, boil it first or buy bottled water.
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> accidental drinking of tap water could cause diarrhea, if this happen please seek professional helps. If you prefer drinking tap water, ask the locals about the region that you are staying at, tap water quality tends 
        to be better in larger developed city.

      </p>
