   <section id="etiquette" class="section">
        <h3>Etiquette</h3>
        <h1>Greetings</h1>
      <img src="/receivingChina.jpg" alt="Greeting" class="smaller-image">
      <p> 
        in China, observing proper greetings and practicing politeness holds significant cultural importance. When addressing individuals, it's customary to use their last name followed by their title, such as "Mr." or "Miss." Initial interactions often involve a handshake, nod, or slight bow, depending on the context. Presenting or receiving items, like business cards, is done with both hands to convey respect. Maintaining appropriate eye contact while 
        conversing and showing genuine interest in others' well-being and experiences are valued gestures. Using formal language and titles, especially when addressing elders or professionals, is a sign of respect. Embracing these customs demonstrates your appreciation for Chinese culture and can foster positive relationships during your time in the country.
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>Tipping culture is not common in China, in restaurants, service charges is included in the bill. Another thing to look out is the language that we use. 
          Do not use informal language when interacting with the locals.  
      </p>
    </div>
    <h1> Body Language</h1>
        <img src="/bodylangChina.jpg" alt="Religious Sites" class="smaller-image">
      <p>
        Non-verbal communication carries considerable weight, body language serves as a powerful means of expression. One particular aspect of this is the practice of refraining from pointing with the index finger, which is widely regarded as impolite. Instead, the Chinese opt for more respectful and subtle gestures. Rather than pointing directly, individuals often employ an open hand, using the entire hand or a gentle wave to indicate a direction or object of interest. 
      </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> 
        This way of communicating reflects a sense of togetherness and prevents any unintended misunderstandings. Another common option is nodding in the direction you're indicating, which is well understood. This custom shows how much importance is placed on cultural awareness, emphasizing the significance of conveying thoughts thoughtfully and respectfully. Incorporating these nuances into your body language not only improves your communication but also displays your regard for local traditions.
      </p>
